Ok, I have been able to verify the issue. It applies to all inline overlays using triggers (modals, popovers). 

When calling `.setRoot()`, the component is rendered from a new instance, which renders the inline modal/popover with the same trigger id. This is problematic, because the trigger element already has a reference to the original overlay.

One way to work around this, is to use unique trigger values, per render.

For example:
```tsx
import { Component, h } from '@stencil/core';

let popoverId = 0;
let modalId = 0;

@Component({
  tag: 'app-home',
  styleUrl: 'app-home.css',
})
export class AppHome {
  setRoot() {
    const nav = document.querySelector('ion-nav');
    nav.setRoot('app-home');
  }

  render() {
    const popoverTrigger = `trigger-popover-button-${++popoverId}`;
    const modalTrigger = `trigger-modal-button-${++modalId}`;
    return [
      <ion-header>
        <ion-toolbar color="primary">
          <ion-title>Home</ion-title>
        </ion-toolbar>
      </ion-header>,

      <ion-content class="ion-padding">
        <ion-button onClick={() => this.setRoot()}>Set Root</ion-button>
        <ion-button id={popoverTrigger}>Click to open popover</ion-button>
        <ion-popover trigger={popoverTrigger}>
          <ion-content>Popover Content</ion-content>
        </ion-popover>
        <ion-button id={modalTrigger}>Click to open modal</ion-button>
        <ion-modal trigger={modalTrigger}>
          <ion-content>modal Content</ion-content>
        </ion-modal>
      </ion-content>,
    ];
  }
}
```

It may be difficult to make the inline overlays aware that the trigger element is disconnected from the overlay. This may just be a usage pattern issue when using `ion-nav` with inline overlays.

