It's not really that simple,

Say for example I have a custom ion-header component that displays as the header on every page/modal. It needs to know whether or not it's displaying in a modal on a page that's not currently hidden by the nav in order to control what goes in the template.

The Javascript for this gets quite complicated, when having to make guesses about when an ion-page might or might not appear.

```
let isActiveModalHeader = false;
const modalEl = this.$el.closest('ion-modal');
if (modalEl) {
	if (modalEl.querySelector(':scope > .modal-wrapper > .ion-page > ion-header, :scope > .modal-wrapper > .ion-page > .ion-page > ion-header') === this.$el) {
		isActiveModalHeader = true;
	}
	modalEl.querySelectorAll(':scope > .modal-wrapper > ion-nav > .ion-page:not(.ion-page-hidden) > ion-header, :scope > .modal-wrapper > .ion-page > ion-nav > .ion-page:not(.ion-page-hidden) > ion-header').forEach((header) => {
		if (this.$el === header) {
			isActiveModalHeader = true;
		}
	});
}
```

The selector specificity is necessary because we don't want to dig down deeper into a case where it's used as a sub-header that may appear on a tab page inside the modal, or a similar case.

Honestly I would think generating clean markup would be motivation enough to fix this, especially since the usage differs between frameworks. Design consistency is valuable in upon itself.

