The modal close animation translates to `100vh` which is 100% of the viewport height, moving the modal off the bottom of the screen. The problem here is that this application has viewport resizing on when the keyboard is open. So when the keyboard is open, 100vh roughly equals `100% of the screen height - the keyboard height`. 

The behavior you are seeing is "correct" because the modal is animating to 100% of the viewport height, but at the point when that value is calculated, the webview is still resized down.

There are a few options in terms of workarounds to try:

1. Disable webview resizing. This may or may not be possible due to requirements in the application.
2. Wrap your dismiss call in a `requestAnimationFrame` to give the webview a chance to resize:

```js
requestAnimationFrame(() => {
  modal.dismiss();
});
```

You might need to do two `requestAnimationFrame` calls if just the one does not work.

While this is not really a bug in Ionic Framework, I will investigate to see if there is something we can do internally to make this work better with resizing viewports.

Using the `requestAnimationFrame()` workaround twice seems to fix the issue in the demo, though in practice, a larger application can vary in terms of speed based on how the code is written as well as how powerful the device performing the action is. In testing on real devices and with a large application, we found that a more consistent approach was to utilize the [ionic keyboard plugin](https://github.com/ionic-team/cordova-plugin-ionic-keyboard). 

Using this plugin, when you would normally call `modal.dismiss()`, you can add an event listener to the keyboard for on hide, then call keyboard hide yourself. Inside the callback for the event, you would then call `modal.dismiss()` . Something akin to:

```typescript
window.addEventListener('keyboardDidHide', async () => {
  await modal.dismiss();
}, { once: true });
Keyboard.hide();
```

One other consideration, you'd only need this on iOS, so it would be worth wrapping that in a platform check.

